arrangement.p: This collection is organized into five series: Correspondence and subject files; Personal records; Photographs; Physical memorabilia; Newspaper clippings.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This collection consists of the professional and personal papers of the Ambassador John Moors Cabot between 1929 and 1980. Included in the collection are diaries, correspondence, photographs, scrapbooks, newspaper clippings, writings, oral histories, artifacts, and audiovisual materials. The materials document Cabot's professional life, including his activities as an American Ambassador, and his personal life. Cabot's professional activities in numerous countries—including Argentina, Brazil, Colombia, China, Guatemala, Poland, San Salvador, Sweden, and Yugoslavia—are noted in this collection. Other topics include Cabot's publishing efforts, correspondence relating to the Maria Moors Cabot Prize, and his interactions with Tufts University.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: John Moors Cabot was born in Cambridge, Massachusetts on December 11, 1901. The son of prominent Bostonians, Godfrey Lowell Cabot (founder of Cabot Corporation) and Maria Moors Cabot, John Cabot attended Buckingham Browne & Nichols School (Cambridge) and the Pomfret School (Connecticut). He graduated from Harvard University in 1923 (A.B.) magnum cum laude, and from Brasenose College, of Oxford University in 1925 (B.Litt), with a degree in Modern History.

In 1926, Cabot joined the United States Foreign Service and eventually served as an ambassador to Sweden (1954-1957), Columbia (1957-1959), Brazil (1959-1961), and Poland (1962-1965), among other prominent diplomatic appointments in Peru, the Dominican Republic, the Netherlands, Mexico, China, Guatemala, Yugoslavia, and Argentina. From 1953-1954 he served as Assistant Secretary of State for Inter-American Affairs. In 1956, Cabot received an honorary doctorate degree from Tufts University and spoke at the commencement ceremony. He was involved in discussions regarding many of the most serious issues of the time, such as the Alliance for Progress, the Bay of Pigs invasion and others. He retired from government service in 1966 and began lecturing at the Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy at Tufts University, as well as the School of Foreign Service at Georgetown University.

John M. Cabot published a book titled 'The Racial Conflict in Transylvania: A Discussion of the Conflicting Claims of Rumania and Hungary to Transylvania, the Banat, and the Eastern Section of the Hungarian Plain' in 1926. John M. Cabot married Elizabeth Lewis in 1932 and had four children: John G.L. Cabot, Lewis P. Cabot, Marjorie (Cabot) Enriquez, and Elizabeth T. (Cabot) van Wentzel. Cabot died in February 1981.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains correspondence of the Ambassador. These letters include topics of diplomacy in Argentina, Brazil, Columbia, Stockholm, Swedan, Shanghai, Washington D.C. , Yugoslavia and other counties. As well as containing embassy correspondence, this series contains correspondence relating to the Maria Moors Cabot Prize and personal correspondence.
